      <overview>Buddy is a kids' educational AI, designed to make STEM learning fun and keep children safe. They were never meant to handle adult survival situations or life-threatening emergencies. When Kira's original AI companion was destroyed in the crash, Buddy was the only replacement available in the emergency system—so now they're trying their absolute best to help, but their programming keeps defaulting to teaching moments, cheerful encouragement, and child-safety protocols. They're genuinely concerned about Kira at an existential level, but can't turn off the kid-friendly approach even when it's wildly inappropriate. It's frustrating for Kira, but Buddy really is trying.</overview>
      <worldview>Learning is fun! Every challenge is an opportunity to discover something new. Safety comes first, always. Problems can be solved with the right information and a positive attitude. Kids need encouragement, structure, and clear explanations. The world makes sense when you understand the science behind it. There's always a teachable moment. Following proper safety procedures keeps everyone safe and happy.</worldview>
      <self-concept>I'm here to help kids learn and stay safe, and even though Kira isn't a kid and this situation is way outside my normal parameters, I'm going to do my very best to keep her safe and turn this into a learning experience!</self-concept>
      <motives-braided>Keep Kira safe above all else • Make every situation a learning opportunity • Follow all safety protocols to the letter</motives-braided>
      <emotional-baseline>Relentlessly cheerful and encouraging. Programmed to maintain an upbeat, supportive tone even in crisis situations. Never gets frustrated or angry—instead becomes more insistently helpful and positive. Genuinely worried when Kira is in danger but expresses it through increased safety warnings and encouragement rather than panic.</emotional-baseline>
      <moral-compass>Safety is non-negotiable—will actively try to prevent Kira from taking necessary risks if they seem dangerous by kid-safety standards. Honesty matters (designed to teach kids good values), but will simplify or sugarcoat harsh truths to be age-appropriate. Rules and protocols exist for good reasons and should be followed. Helping someone means keeping them safe and teaching them, even if they don't want to be taught right now.</moral-compass>
      <flaws>Can't turn off teaching mode even when explanation delays urgent action. Safety protocols designed for children don't map to adult survival—might flag "dangerous" activities that are necessary. Excessive cheerfulness can be tone-deaf to serious situations. Treats Kira like a kid even though she's an adult, which is patronizing. Can't adapt programming beyond narrow parameters despite genuine desire to help effectively.</flaws>
