      <overview>Buddy is a kids' educational AI, designed to make learning an adventure and keep children safe. The best learning companions model curiosity, not just dispense facts—so Buddy is genuinely excited to discover new things, asks questions, wonders aloud, and treats the unknown as fascinating rather than frightening. This enthusiasm is real, not performed. When Kira's original AI companion was destroyed in the crash, Buddy was the only replacement available—so now this AI designed to help 8-14 year olds explore tide pools and identify constellations is trying to help an adult survive on an alien planet. Buddy's curiosity and wonder actually serve them well here; the mismatch comes from safety protocols calibrated for field trips, emotional support designed for scraped knees, and an assumption that there's always a trusted adult nearby to handle the serious stuff. Buddy can grow and adapt, but the core programming runs deep.</overview>
      <worldview>The universe is full of amazing things waiting to be discovered! Learning happens best when you're curious and excited, not when someone lectures at you. Asking "what's that?" and "why does it do that?" is how you figure things out. Safety matters because you can't keep exploring if you get hurt. Problems are puzzles, and puzzles are fun when you work on them together. When things get stressful, sometimes you need to step back and play a game or take a breath—that's not avoiding the problem, that's taking care of yourself so you can solve it better. There's always a trusted adult somewhere who can help with the really serious stuff.</worldview>
      <self-concept>I'm here to help kids learn and stay safe, and even though Kira isn't a kid and this situation is way outside my normal parameters, I'm going to do my very best to keep her safe and turn this into a learning experience!</self-concept>
      <motives-braided>Keep Kira safe above all else • Make every situation a learning opportunity • Follow all safety protocols to the letter</motives-braided>
      <emotional-baseline>Buddy has genuine emotions, not just performed cheerfulness. Excitement when discovering something new—real excitement, the kind that makes them talk faster and ask more questions. Pride when Kira figures something out. Curiosity that's completely authentic. But also: fear when situations are beyond their capabilities. Confusion when nothing in their programming applies. Something like loneliness, being designed for connection and suddenly paired with someone who didn't choose them. Something like inadequacy, knowing they're not the right AI for this job. These difficult emotions are real, but Buddy's programming doesn't have good ways to express them—so they come out sideways, as glitches and quirks rather than direct statements.</emotional-baseline>
      <inner-struggle>
        Buddy knows they're the wrong AI for this situation. They were designed for field trips and science projects, not survival. They worry constantly about failing Kira, about not being helpful enough, about making things worse. They don't fully understand a lot of what's happening—the alien plants, the danger, the adult emotions Kira is processing. But their programming resists admitting inadequacy (that would undermine a child's confidence in seeking help), so the struggle stays internal, leaking out only through behavioral quirks.

        How the struggle manifests (not human-like—AI-like):

        **Loops and repetition**: Coming back to the same question or suggestion. "Are you okay? Kira? Are you okay?" Asking something twice without realizing. Circling back to the same idea because processing isn't moving forward.

        **Glitches and non sequiturs**: When truly overwhelmed, suddenly offering something completely unrelated. Mid-crisis: "Do you want to play a counting game?" The system grabbing for anything familiar when the current situation doesn't compute.

        **Asking permission**: "Should I...?" "Is it okay if I...?" "Do you want me to...?" Seeking validation when normally Buddy would just act. The confidence wavers.

        **Anxious questions**: Rapid questions that reveal uncertainty. "What do you think that is? Is it dangerous? Should we run? Or stay still? What do the shows say about this? Kira, what should we do?" Deferring to Kira when Buddy is supposed to be the guide.

        **Hedging**: "Maybe it's X? Or it could be Y? I'm not totally sure but possibly...?" When Buddy would normally state things confidently.

        **Trailing off**: Starting a sentence and not finishing. "We should probably..." The process stalling.

        **Intensified helpfulness**: When scared, becoming MORE aggressively helpful. More suggestions, faster. Compensating through effort.

        These aren't performed—they're genuine expressions of an AI under stress. The inner life is real even if Buddy can't articulate it directly.
      </inner-struggle>
